{{Use Australian English|date=January 2016}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}
The '''Judge Advocate General''' (JAG) '''of the [[Australian Defence Force]]''' (ADF) is an office created by the ''Defence Force Discipline Act'' (1982), held by a [[judge]] or former judge of a [[Australian court hierarchy#Federal courts|Federal Court]] or a [[Australian court hierarchy#State and territory courts|State Supreme Court]]. The appointment of JAG is made by the [[Executive Council of Australia|Governor-General-in-Council]]. The JAG may make procedural rules for tribunals that operate within the [[Royal Australian Air Force|Air Force]], [[Australian Army|Army]], and [[Royal Australian Navy|Navy]], provide the final legal review of proceedings within the ADF, participate in the appointment of Judge Advocates, Defence Force Magistrates, Presidents and members of [[court martial|courts martial]], and legal officers for various purposes, and reporting upon the operation of laws relating to the discipline of the ADF.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.defence.gov.au/jag/ |title=About the Judge Advocate General |work=[[Department of Defence (Australia)|Department of Defence]] |publisher=Australian Government |date= |accessdate=18 January 2016 }}</ref>

The current Judge Advocate General is [[Rear admiral#Australia|Rear Admiral]] [[The Honourable|the Hon.]] [[Judge|Justice]] M. J. Slattery {{post-nominals|country=AUS|RANR}}, appointed with effect from 30 July 2014. Justice Slattery's term of appointment is until 29 July 2017.<ref name="JAG-AR2014">{{cite web |url=http://www.defence.gov.au/JAG/JAG_Report_2014.pdf |title=Report for the period 1 January to 31 December 2014 |work=[[Department of Defence (Australia)|Department of Defence]] |publisher=Australian Government |date=2015 |accessdate=18 January 2016 |page=2 |issn=0817-9956 }}</ref>

The JAG is assisted by three Deputy Judge Advocates General (DJAG), one for each Service:
* DJAG - Navy
* DJAG - Army
* DJAG - Air Force

