The '''Truce of Calais''' was a truce agreed to by King [[Edward III of England]] and King [[Philip IV of France]] on 28 September 1347, that was mediated by [[Pope Clement VI]]. In November 1348 the Truce of Calais was extended for a further twelve months and again in May 1349. The truce was extended over the years and lasted till 1355.{{sfn|Wagner|2006|pp=74–75}} The truce did not stop the on-going naval clashes between the two countries and the fighting in Gascony and Brittany.
